  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Doctors are being cautioned not to routinely prescribe aspirin in the prevention of heart attacks.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   This word from the Food and Drug Administration comes
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   after findings which suggest that aspirin therapy may increase the possibility of stroke in some patients.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Individuals most at risk are those with blood clotting problems or high blood pressure.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   This warning comes after a study, published in January,
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   which indicated that an aspirin taken every other day reduced the risk of a non-fatal first heart attack by 47 percent as compared to a group taking a non-aspirin substitute.
  </a>
